{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c16e64a-5864-49ce-978e-9680ad084c13","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for the process name.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — If enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited` before running), they land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nSince NativeAOT produces a native binary (not managed), macOS treats it like any other native crash and generates a standard Apple crash report with a stack trace, register state, and loaded images. The `.ips` files are JSON-formatted and usually the quickest way to triage.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75844284-643c-4cd8-bd7d-d0f9737d9258","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"1BC0:1290CA:E3BC83:1031131:6A028693"},"id":"fb979856-c8a1-4209-955a-342bedfd7eda","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:08.678Z","parentId":"c02b2ef6-ffed-47b5-b170-0ed6c641f2da"}
